To check the general availability of this synthetic strategy in Fig. 1, different leaves of six plants (camphor, bamboo, cassia, willow, orange, and magnolia) were used as raw materials to synthesize SCDs. Although different leaves had different compositions, they all contained large amounts of cellulose and hemicellulose that were the major common precursor to provide the similar structures and properties of SCDs. The catalytic performance of these SCDs for converting fructose to HMF is shown in Fig. 7
                        . In all cases, the fructose was completely consumed to give HMF yields of 89.2%–93.5% under the same reaction conditions, suggesting that common plant leaves could serve as a sustainable feedstock for producing highly active SCD catalysts. Compared with many kinds of carbon-based catalyst or organocatalyst in previous report (Table 1
                        ), the highest yield of HMF was obtained when using the SCDs as catalyst, indicating the superior activity of SCDs for selective conversion of fructose to HMF.
